The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, August 03, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Aug. 2: The special savings scheme for senior citizens offering a 9 per cent return will be launched in a day or two. A notification would be issued shortly, finance ministry sources said today. The scheme would have an upper investment ceiling of Rs 15 lakh and it would be in the form of a bond. The bonds, for persons above 60 years, would be taxable.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 2: Admitting that a hike in petrol and diesel prices will have a one-time impact on inflation, the finance ministry today said the price level is likely to stabilise with signs of improved monsoon. 																								 Mumbai, Aug. 2: The initial public offering of Tata Consultancy Services was today oversubscribed 2.54 times of the issue size of 5.54 crore shares. The book-built issue received cumulative bids (BSE and NSE) for 14.08 crore shares with bidders initially opting for a price range of Rs 775 to Rs 800 per share. 																								 New Delhi, Aug. 2: The National Council of Applied Economic Research today pegged downward the GDP growth projection for 2004-05 to 6.54 from 6.74 per cent due to a lower-than-expected farm sector growth following delayed monsoons. 																								 Mumbai, Aug. 2: Former Reserve Bank governor I. G. Patel and Nicholas Piramal India Ltd chairman Ajay Piramal have resigned from State Banks central board.
